install the first one without problems, then hit the same plug-in and try to 
reinstall on top and 'almost' do it, except that rename fails because 
plugin.xml already exists.

This particular problem will probably go away when the duplication is removed.

An orthogonal issue is that we didn't warn about this.

In 2.1, we can handle this problem in two ways:

1) Compute the list of plug-ins we want to install beforehand and do not allow 
install because of duplications
2) As we install, keep track of plug-ins/fragments we already handled so that 
we don't do things multiple times.

I prefer solution 2) because it is more tolerant. If both plug-ins are exact 
same ID and version, we can assume that we did it alrady and don't need to
do it again.

What would be interesting to find out is if we actually downloaded the same 
plug-in twice (i.e. move the bytes over the network).

To be clear: duplications of this type are provider error. The issue is simply
if we will flag it and give up during the pre-install check, or just keep
track of plug-ins and do not install them twice. In large products with
hundreds of plug-ins, things like this one are bound to happen.

Having the same plugin/fragment appear in multiple features is a strong 
requirement.  My understanding from Dejan (previously) is that this is expected 
behaviour.

Features are NOT a containment model.  Anyone can define a feature to be 
whatever they want.  Different products from different (or the same) vendor 
will trivially need to reference the same plugins (e.g., EMF, GEF, ...) which 
are not part of some standard base install (e.g., the Eclipse Platform).  

One could reasonably argue that people should be referencing/including the 
EMF/GEF/... features rather than the specific plugins.  Ideally yes but only if 
the original producers of the features foresaw the consumer's requirements and 
packaged just the plugins that would be needed.  In practice consumer 
requirements vary widely and this is unlikely.  There are several product 
scenarios today which require overlapping features.

I believe this should be fixed for 2.1.
